@page "/components/data-display/barcodes/accessibility"
@layout MainLayout
@using Sunfish.UIAdapters.Blazor.Components.Showcase

<PageTitle>Barcodes / Accessibility · Sunfish Kitchen Sink</PageTitle>

<SunfishExamplePanel Title="Barcodes / Accessibility"
                     Breadcrumb="@_breadcrumb"
                     GitHubUrl="https://github.com/ctwoodwa/Sunfish/blob/main/apps/kitchen-sink/Pages/Components/DataDisplay/Barcodes/Accessibility/Demo.razor"
                     Sources="@GeneratedSources">

    <Narrative>
        <p>
            A barcode is a visual encoding of a text value — by itself it carries no semantic
            meaning for a screen reader or for a user who cannot see it. The single most
            important accessibility rule for barcode components is therefore
            <strong>WCAG 1.1.1 Non-text Content</strong>: the rendered output must expose the
            encoded value as text, so the information is available without relying on a scanner
            camera or on sight.
        </p>
        <p>
            <code>SunfishBarcode</code> renders an inline <code>&lt;svg role="img"&gt;</code> with
            an auto-generated <code>aria-label</code> of the form <em>"Barcode: &lt;value&gt;"</em>,
            so the encoded value is always announced. Setting <code>ShowLabel="true"</code>
            (default) also prints the value as visible sibling text for sighted users who cannot
            scan the code. Keep both on whenever the value is user-meaningful (order number,
            SKU); use only the label when the raw SVG bars are decorative or the value is
            displayed as data elsewhere.
        </p>
    </Narrative>

    <Example>
        <div style="display:flex; flex-direction:column; gap:1.75rem;">

            <section>
                <h3 style="margin:0 0 .5rem 0; font-size:.9rem; opacity:.7; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:.05em;">Default — text alternative + visible label</h3>
                <p style="margin:.25rem 0 .75rem 0; font-size:.9rem;">
                    <code>aria-label</code> contains the encoded value, and
                    <code>ShowLabel="true"</code> prints it underneath. This is the baseline —
                    never ship a barcode without both unless the value is redundant with nearby
                    text.
                </p>
                <SunfishBarcode Value="SUNFISH-0001"
                                Type="BarcodeType.Code128"
                                Height="70"
                                ShowLabel="true" />
            </section>

            <section>
                <h3 style="margin:0 0 .5rem 0; font-size:.9rem; opacity:.7; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:.05em;">Figure pattern — value exposed via caption</h3>
                <p style="margin:.25rem 0 .75rem 0; font-size:.9rem;">
                    When the barcode is a piece of content rather than an inline label, wrap it
                    in a <code>&lt;figure&gt;</code> / <code>&lt;figcaption&gt;</code> and use
                    <code>aria-labelledby</code> to name it explicitly. This reads as
                    <em>"Figure, Order SUNFISH-0001"</em> instead of the raw value alone.
                </p>
                <figure style="margin:0; display:inline-flex; flex-direction:column; gap:.5rem; align-items:flex-start;">
                    <SunfishBarcode Value="SUNFISH-0001"
                                    Type="BarcodeType.Code128"
                                    Height="70"
                                    ShowLabel="false"
                                    aria-labelledby="bc-cap-order" />
                    <figcaption id="bc-cap-order" style="font-size:.85rem;">
                        Order number <strong>SUNFISH-0001</strong>
                    </figcaption>
                </figure>
            </section>

            <section>
                <h3 style="margin:0 0 .5rem 0; font-size:.9rem; opacity:.7; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:.05em;">Don't: barcode-only with no text alternative</h3>
                <p style="margin:.25rem 0 .75rem 0; font-size:.9rem;">
                    Avoid rendering the SVG bars while hiding the value. Even though
                    <code>SunfishBarcode</code> adds a default <code>aria-label</code>, a user
                    who cannot decode the bars should never depend on that alone when the value
                    is important business data.
                </p>
                <div style="display:flex; flex-direction:column; gap:.5rem; padding:.75rem; border:1px dashed #c5a000; border-radius:.375rem; background:#fffbeb;">
                    <SunfishBarcode Value="SUNFISH-0001"
                                    Type="BarcodeType.Code128"
                                    Height="70"
                                    ShowLabel="false" />
                    <span style="font-size:.8rem; color:#78350f;">
                        Anti-pattern — the visible value is missing. Fix by setting
                        <code>ShowLabel="true"</code> or adding a visible caption / adjacent text.
                    </span>
                </div>
            </section>

            <section>
                <h3 style="margin:0 0 .5rem 0; font-size:.9rem; opacity:.7; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:.05em;">Color contrast &amp; high-contrast</h3>
                <p style="margin:.25rem 0 .75rem 0; font-size:.9rem;">
                    Bars need high contrast against their surface for both scanners and users
                    with low vision. Default is black on transparent; if you override
                    <code>Color</code>, verify the bar / background pair meets at least 3:1
                    (WCAG 1.4.11 Non-text Contrast).
                </p>
                <div style="display:flex; gap:1.5rem; flex-wrap:wrap;">
                    <div>
                        <SunfishBarcode Value="HIGH-CONTRAST"
                                        Color="#000000"
                                        Height="70" />
                        <div style="font-size:.8rem; margin-top:.25rem;">Black on white — passes.</div>
                    </div>
                    <div style="background:#111; padding:.75rem;">
                        <SunfishBarcode Value="HIGH-CONTRAST"
                                        Color="#ffffff"
                                        Height="70" />
                        <div style="font-size:.8rem; margin-top:.25rem; color:#fff;">White on black — passes.</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </section>

            <section>
                <h3 style="margin:0 0 .5rem 0; font-size:.9rem; opacity:.7; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:.05em;">ARIA &amp; semantic contract</h3>
                <dl style="display:grid; grid-template-columns: max-content 1fr; column-gap:1rem; row-gap:.35rem; margin:0; font-size:.875rem;">
                    <dt><code>role="img"</code></dt>
                    <dd>Applied to the inner <code>&lt;svg&gt;</code> so screen readers treat it as a single graphic with a name.</dd>
                    <dt><code>aria-label="Barcode: {Value}"</code></dt>
                    <dd>Auto-generated — the encoded value is always in the accessibility tree.</dd>
                    <dt><code>ShowLabel="true"</code> (default)</dt>
                    <dd>Renders the value as visible text inside the SVG; required when the barcode is the user's only view of the value.</dd>
                    <dt><strong>WCAG 1.1.1 Non-text Content</strong></dt>
                    <dd>Satisfied by the combination of <code>aria-label</code> + visible label. Both paths expose the same text.</dd>
                    <dt><strong>WCAG 1.4.1 Use of Color</strong></dt>
                    <dd>The encoded information is not communicated by color — only by bar pattern and the text label.</dd>
                    <dt><strong>WCAG 1.4.11 Non-text Contrast</strong></dt>
                    <dd>Bar color must reach 3:1 against the surface — verify any custom <code>Color</code> override.</dd>
                    <dt><strong>Keyboard</strong></dt>
                    <dd>Barcode is purely decorative output — not focusable. Interactive scanners, print buttons, etc. are layered on top and carry their own semantics.</dd>
                </dl>
            </section>

            <section>
                <h3 style="margin:0 0 .5rem 0; font-size:.9rem; opacity:.7; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:.05em;">Known gaps</h3>
                <ul style="margin:0; font-size:.875rem;">
                    <li>The MVP Code128 encoder is deterministic but not a scannable payload — the
                        a11y contract (text alternative) is unaffected, but production
                        scan-accuracy work is pending.</li>
                    <li>Only <code>Code128</code> and <code>Code39</code> are implemented on the
                        <code>DataDisplay/SunfishBarcode</code> surface today. Other symbologies
                        (QR, DataMatrix, EAN) are planned — the text-alternative rule applies
                        identically to all of them.</li>
                </ul>
            </section>

        </div>
    </Example>

</SunfishExamplePanel>

@code {
    private static readonly string[] _breadcrumb =
        ["Components", "Data Display", "Barcodes", "Accessibility"];
}
